# === Server ===
NODE_ENV=development
PORT=3000

# === Supabase ===
# Get these from: supabase.com → your project → Settings → API
SUPABASE_URL=https://your-project-id.supabase.co
SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=your_anon_key_here
SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY=your_service_role_key_here

# === JWT ===
# Generate with: openssl rand -base64 32
JWT_SECRET=replace_with_minimum_32_character_random_string

# === Storage ===
STORAGE_BUCKET_ACTIVITIES=activity-assets
SIGNED_URL_EXPIRY_SECONDS=300

# === CORS ===
# Comma separated list of allowed origins
ALLOWED_ORIGINS=http://localhost:3000

# === Rate Limiting ===
RATE_LIMIT_WINDOW_MS=60000
RATE_LIMIT_MAX_REQUESTS=100

# === Stripe (scaffold only — implement after launch) ===
STRIPE_SECRET_KEY=sk_test_placeholder
STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET=whsec_placeholder
```

Now create your **real** `.env` file — copy `.env.example` and rename the copy to `.env`. Then fill in your real Supabase values. This `.env` file will never be committed because of the `.gitignore` you just created.
```
Minigenius_backend/
  node_modules/
  .env                ✅ ← your real secrets, never committed
  .env.example        ✅ ← safe template, committed to Git
  .gitignore          ✅
  package.json        ✅
  tsconfig.json       ✅